PlatinumSrc - A dead simple game engine
(C) 2026- Sam W. & Other Contributors
================================================================================

Welcome to the repository for PlatinumSrc, a game engine and collection
of tools built with a unique goal in mind, limits. Not what most people
would even consider reasonable, but _actual_, miserable limits that force
highly efficient, compact code that squeezes every possible ounce of raw
performance.

 |
 | PlatinumSrc is designed to work on systems as dated as a Pentium 4
 | class system, running x86 Windows XP. PlatinumSrc is expected to run
 | on hardware around this spec:
 | -> Windows XP x86 (x64 MIGHT work)
 | -> Intel Pentium 4 505 ~@ 2.66GHz
 | -> > 368MB usable RAM
 | -> ATI Radeon 9000 series GPU (at least 64MB of vRAM) 
 |

And that's the goal. If you have a PC of similar spec and age, you should
be able to compile the source code on that machine and even the engine
examples, _and_ run them! Now most actual development happens on _modern_
hardware, alongside compiling and testing but if you have physical hardware
and it's in a usable state, you absolutely should test on it!

You don't have to directly compile on the target hardware, though if you do...
prepare for long compiling times, as those PCs are dated and aren't really
optimized for building like this, heh.

Technical Stuffs
================================================================================

PlatinumSrc is implemented in C99 with no compiler extensions. Just plain C.
To avoid what could be problematic, a lot of _required things_ like libraries
for math, utilities, and whatever else we need, are implemented "in-house"
...AKA: we do it ourselves or rely on minimal dependencies. Exceptions exist, 
like graphics, that's handled externally to avoid what would be actual years of 
developer hell.

PlatinumSrc uses OpenGL 2.1 for graphics and GLSL 110 for shaders. Basic but
effectively universal, works anywhere, except on MacOS which is probably going
to break in the near future.

** To build on Windows **

In a "Visual Studio Developer Command Prompt" - run `build.cmd`
 >> Not powershell, classic command prompt

Remember to read the top-level comments to know what you need before runing!

** To build on Linux / macOS **

Just use the Makefile!

